45:54.085 --> 45:58.955
<i>Knowing I had to walk up those
 stairs was a lonely feeling.</i>

45:58.957 --> 46:00.823
- Where you going?

46:00.825 --> 46:01.991
- Up.

46:04.095 --> 46:06.162
- I'm going with you.

46:09.267 --> 46:11.934
<i> - When we reached
 the first landing</i>

46:11.936 --> 46:14.904
<i> I could see the face
 of a young boy.</i>

46:14.906 --> 46:16.372
- Good Lord.

46:16.374 --> 46:19.942
<i> - His eyes were open
 and he was dead.</i>

46:19.944 --> 46:21.778
<i> I quickly turned around
 the corner</i>

46:21.780 --> 46:24.981
<i> and I saw a young woman,</i>

46:24.983 --> 46:27.316
<i> a dead young woman,
 lying at his feet.</i>

46:29.320 --> 46:32.221
<i> And there was another woman
 lying there,</i>

46:32.223 --> 46:36.025
<i> and we...we turned her
 on her side</i>

46:36.027 --> 46:39.228
to keep her from drowning
in her own blood.

46:39.230 --> 46:41.531
<i> There was a young man
 that was wounded.</i>

46:41.533 --> 46:44.901
<i> Slumped against the wall,
 still conscious.</i>

46:44.903 --> 46:47.236
- The boy that was at
the foot of the stairs saw us.

46:48.907 --> 46:52.241
And Martinez and I asked him

46:52.243 --> 46:54.243
how many people
were shooting.

46:55.914 --> 46:59.081
[clears throat]
And he replied, "One."

46:59.083 --> 47:02.552
<i> - He said, "He's outside."
 [gunshot]</i>

47:02.554 --> 47:04.554
<i> And he pointed upstairs.</i>

47:09.260 --> 47:11.260
<i> [gunshots]</i>

47:13.464 --> 47:15.164
- So we playing for keeps?

47:16.935 --> 47:18.267
- Damn right we are.

47:19.604 --> 47:22.605
- I guess you better
deputize me, then.

47:22.607 --> 47:25.174
<i> - I looked at him and...</i>

47:25.176 --> 47:30.913
I thought he was an officer
from some other agency.

47:30.915 --> 47:32.949
Consider yourself deputized.

47:35.453 --> 47:37.954
All right, ready?

47:37.956 --> 47:39.288
- I'll cover you.

47:43.294 --> 47:47.296
<i> We worked our way
 into the room...</i>

47:49.968 --> 47:53.002
<i> And found a woman lying
 on her back behind the sofa.</i>

47:57.175 --> 48:00.176
<i>- Gotta keep going.
 [gunshots]</i>

48:08.987 --> 48:12.989
The shooting outside sounded
just like rolling thunder.

48:12.991 --> 48:14.991
<i> [gunshots]</i>

48:18.162 --> 48:19.295
You got me?

48:20.465 --> 48:21.497
- I got you.

48:24.002 --> 48:25.501
<i> Martinez went to the door</i>

48:25.503 --> 48:27.970
<i> and he had trouble
 getting the door open.</i>

48:32.143 --> 48:35.211
- Well, time's passing,
but...

48:37.015 --> 48:40.316
<i> You don't feel like
 time's passing.</i>

48:40.318 --> 48:42.018
Do you understand that?

48:44.489 --> 48:46.355
<i> [gunshots]</i>

48:54.365 --> 48:57.466
- Let's go.
You need to cover that corner.

48:57.468 --> 49:00.303
If anyone comes around there,
you shoot 'em.

49:00.305 --> 49:02.305
<i> [gunshots]</i>

49:05.076 --> 49:08.077
<i> [gentle piano music]</i>

49:08.079 --> 49:11.080
<i> [Debussy's "Clair de Lune"]</i>

49:11.082 --> 49:18.087
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

49:22.193 --> 49:23.592
- I'm going to cover
this corner.

49:23.594 --> 49:25.594
Your fellow officer
went down this way.

49:25.596 --> 49:28.030
- Crum said,
"Are you going to go out

49:28.032 --> 49:29.665
and help
your fellow officer?"

49:29.667 --> 49:33.502
Guess I--Guess I ain't
got much choice now, do I?

49:41.512 --> 49:45.014
<i> - I turned and saw an officer
 I knew, Houston McCoy.</i>

49:45.016 --> 49:49.018
All I had was my .38,
so that--that shotgun

49:49.020 --> 49:51.354
looked pretty beautiful
at that moment.

49:53.358 --> 49:55.157
Get down.

49:55.159 --> 49:56.459
<i> [gunshot]</i>

50:07.472 --> 50:09.205
- The other two officers
went this way.

50:09.207 --> 50:10.373
I'll cover you.
- Got it.

50:11.542 --> 50:13.776
<i> - A picture came to my mind.</i>

50:13.778 --> 50:15.311
My boys and my wife.

50:17.648 --> 50:20.383
<i> And immediately
 it went out of my mind.</i>

50:24.288 --> 50:25.421
I didn't have a fear

50:25.423 --> 50:28.090
of being killed,
I really didn't.

50:28.092 --> 50:31.594
- There was no time
to think about fear.

50:33.331 --> 50:35.798
Now, I'd be a fool
or I'd be a liar

50:35.800 --> 50:39.335
if I were to say
I was not scared.

50:39.337 --> 50:41.437
I was scared.

50:41.439 --> 50:44.440
But you put that behind you.

50:44.442 --> 50:50.112
You cannot have fear in front
of you and do your job.

50:50.114 --> 50:51.614
- I just knew
that I wasn't going to allow

50:51.616 --> 50:53.649
anybody to make me dead.

50:53.651 --> 50:55.751
- I heard the subject
running on the walkway.

50:55.753 --> 50:59.288
I fired one round
in an attempt to stop him.

51:01.626 --> 51:05.428
- What the hell?
- I'm sorry!

51:05.430 --> 51:08.297
I heard him run
the other direction.

51:10.134 --> 51:11.467
<i> - It's going to take longer</i>

51:11.469 --> 51:13.069
to tell you
than it did to do it.

51:14.739 --> 51:16.439
- I emptied my gun.

51:30.288 --> 51:32.455
- There was some firing,

51:32.457 --> 51:34.457
and then it was all over.

51:37.128 --> 51:39.128
<i> [gunshots]</i>

51:56.514 --> 51:58.814
- By the time
I had emptied my pistol...

51:58.816 --> 52:01.217
- By the time
I had emptied my pistol...

52:01.219 --> 52:02.685
- McCoy fired.

52:02.687 --> 52:04.887
- McCoy was pretty close--
I grabbed that shotgun

52:04.889 --> 52:06.889
from McCoy and I shot him

52:06.891 --> 52:09.158
one more time
as he was hitting the ground.

52:12.663 --> 52:14.497
<i> After that was done,</i>

52:14.499 --> 52:18.334
my knees felt like rubber.

52:18.336 --> 52:21.871
I felt like I had been hit
by a sledgehammer.

52:21.873 --> 52:23.772
I mean all my energy left me.

52:23.774 --> 52:28.410
And I was shaking. Rounds,
bullets were still coming up.

52:30.348 --> 52:34.183
And I said I had enough
and I left.

52:34.185 --> 52:35.784
<i> - The campus,
 for all practical purposes,</i>

52:35.786 --> 52:37.453
<i> has been cleared.</i>

52:37.455 --> 52:39.188
<i> Police got to the Tower,
 and are keeping</i>

52:39.190 --> 52:41.357
<i> all the persons
 in the University Tower,</i>

52:41.359 --> 52:42.691
<i> and the main police
 are coming out</i>

52:42.693 --> 52:44.527
<i>and walking across the campus.</i>

52:44.529 --> 52:46.362
<i> The University area
 has been cordoned off.</i>

52:46.364 --> 52:48.531
<i> - I waved my handkerchief
 to stop the firing</i>

52:48.533 --> 52:50.699
<i> from down on the ground.
 [gunshots continue]</i>

52:57.208 --> 52:59.875
- Once that flag waved,
I knew it was over then.

53:02.246 --> 53:05.181
It was bam-bam-bam-bam.
It was just...

53:05.183 --> 53:07.416
'Cause we had--
You had dozens of gunmen

53:07.418 --> 53:09.752
firing at the Tower
from all directions.

53:09.754 --> 53:12.354
<i> And they slowly stopped.</i>

53:12.356 --> 53:13.522
<i> - Ladies and gentlemen,
 we have this word</i>

53:13.524 --> 53:15.257
<i> just into the newsroom.</i>

53:15.259 --> 53:17.593
<i> The sniper has been seen
 waving a white flag</i>

53:17.595 --> 53:19.428
<i> on the west side
 of the building.</i>

53:19.430 --> 53:21.597
<i> According to reports
 just into our newsroom,</i>

53:21.599 --> 53:23.766
<i> the sniper has been seen
 waving a white flag</i>

53:23.768 --> 53:26.769
<i> on the west side
 of the building.</i>

53:26.771 --> 53:29.772
This is Neal Spelce
with a bulletin

53:29.774 --> 53:31.774
from the KTBC Radio newsroom.

53:31.776 --> 53:33.609
The sniper is dead.

53:33.611 --> 53:35.277
<i> This is Neal Spelce
 with a bulletin</i>

53:35.279 --> 53:36.745
<i> from the KTBC Radio newsroom.</i>

53:36.747 --> 53:38.614
<i> The sniper is dead.</i>

53:38.616 --> 53:42.451
<i> The firing has now stopped,
 and the time is 1:23.</i>

53:42.453 --> 53:43.619
<i> [radio shuts off]</i>

53:46.791 --> 53:51.927
When I said, "The sniper
is dead," it was like...

53:51.929 --> 53:55.464
- It was like a big...
[exhales]

53:55.466 --> 53:58.334
Sigh of relief.

53:58.336 --> 54:01.503
The sirens all of a sudden
started getting silent.

54:01.505 --> 54:03.739
The bullets stopped.

54:05.743 --> 54:07.443
<i> And it was quiet.</i>

54:09.447 --> 54:12.481
<i> - Someone waved a flag.</i>

54:12.483 --> 54:16.252
And...I walked around.

54:17.588 --> 54:19.288
<i> There was blood everywhere.</i>

54:22.793 --> 54:25.561
People just surged
out of the building.

54:25.563 --> 54:27.796
- We all walked up the steps.

54:30.434 --> 54:33.002
It seems like
we filled the mall.

54:58.562 --> 55:00.329
<i>- It was a few people at first,</i>

55:00.331 --> 55:01.730
and then dozens,
and then hundreds.

55:06.570 --> 55:08.404
<i> - I don't remember anyone</i>

55:08.406 --> 55:11.607
being articulate
about what had happened.

55:13.444 --> 55:16.945
<i> You know,
 just shock and awe.</i>

55:16.947 --> 55:19.081
Kind of a blankness.

55:23.087 --> 55:25.621
<i> - They looked like
 they were mesmerized.</i>

55:27.958 --> 55:30.092
They-they weren't
hugging each other.

55:30.094 --> 55:34.763
They weren't talking
to each other.

55:34.765 --> 55:38.033
<i> Most of them were
 just kind of milling,</i>

55:38.035 --> 55:41.904
<i> walking around,
 as if dazed and wondering,</i>

55:41.906 --> 55:45.641
"What in the world
has happened to my world?"

55:47.778 --> 55:49.378
<i> [camera clicking]</i>

55:57.388 --> 56:00.556
<i> - They didn't know the names
 of the people who had died.</i>

56:00.558 --> 56:02.591
And we didn't know
what had happened

56:02.593 --> 56:03.992
until later that day.

56:06.564 --> 56:09.932
<i> It was a sad time,
 a very sad time.</i>

56:09.934 --> 56:11.533
Not only for the people
who lost

56:11.535 --> 56:13.402
or were losing
their loved ones,

56:13.404 --> 56:17.873
but for the whole campus,
the whole town, and the state.

56:17.875 --> 56:19.708
- It was not something

56:19.710 --> 56:22.811
you would expect
from our beautiful Tower.

56:27.818 --> 56:30.986
<i> - I just sat there
 and watched people gather.</i>

56:32.790 --> 56:34.656
<i> It was something
 that I had been a part of</i>

56:34.658 --> 56:36.658
<i> for an hour and a half.</i>

56:38.662 --> 56:40.129
<i> It was done for me.</i>

56:40.131 --> 56:42.131
<i> [sirens wailing]</i>

56:44.835 --> 56:46.502
<i> - The Travis County
 Blood Bank</i>

56:46.504 --> 56:48.103
<i> has asked
 to please come immediately.</i>

56:48.105 --> 56:50.973
<i> There is an urgent need
 for these types of blood--</i>

56:50.975 --> 56:52.741
<i> Type O-positive,</i>

56:52.743 --> 56:56.111
<i> Type O-negative,
 Type A-positive.</i>

56:56.113 --> 56:58.814
<i> - I was begging them
 not to cut off my dress</i>

56:58.816 --> 57:02.117
because it was
the first day I'd worn it.

57:02.119 --> 57:06.655
It was my first
and only maternity dress.

57:06.657 --> 57:09.658
<i> It was very beautiful.
Tom had helped me pick it out.</i>

57:12.997 --> 57:15.798
<i> - My dad was working downtown
 in a shoe-repair shop,</i>

57:15.800 --> 57:17.566
<i> and then somebody
 came up to him</i>

57:17.568 --> 57:19.635
<i> and asked him
 if he knew what was going on.</i>

57:19.637 --> 57:22.805
My dad said no.
And the guy said,

57:22.807 --> 57:25.741
"Well, there's been
a lot of shooting going on."

57:25.743 --> 57:27.709
- He said, "Yeah, there's
a lot of shooting going on.

57:27.711 --> 57:29.077
"And, oh, by the way,

57:29.079 --> 57:33.015
your son has been shot
and he was killed."

57:33.017 --> 57:35.551
He went home, picked up my mom,
and the two of 'em

57:35.553 --> 57:37.052
rushed over to the hospital.

57:37.054 --> 57:40.722
He-he did not want
to believe that...

57:40.724 --> 57:43.892
until it was something
that he-he could...

57:43.894 --> 57:45.727
that could be confirmed.

57:45.729 --> 57:50.899
Whereas my mother
was responding...

57:50.901 --> 57:54.603
I guess like a mother.

57:54.605 --> 58:00.776
<i>My parents didn't find out for
several hours that I was okay.</i>

58:00.778 --> 58:02.978
<i> - It's a madhouse here
 at Brackenridge Hospital.</i>

58:02.980 --> 58:05.848
<i> At least 17 persons are here
 undergoing treatment.</i>

58:05.850 --> 58:09.084
<i>We have had unconfirmed reports
 that two persons have died.</i>

58:09.086 --> 58:10.752
<i> We have a list of the names.</i>

58:10.754 --> 58:12.120
<i> These names were
 just given to us</i>

58:12.122 --> 58:14.022
<i> by the hospital
 administrator.</i>

58:14.024 --> 58:16.925
<i> The victims have been
 identified as Oscar Royuela,</i>

58:16.927 --> 58:19.094
<i> Billy Speed, Robert Boyer,</i>

58:19.096 --> 58:22.764
<i> Paul Sonntag,
 Roy Schmidt, Billy Snowden--</i>

58:22.766 --> 58:24.933
<i>- Joe, hold it.
 Hold just a minute.</i>

58:24.935 --> 58:26.602
<i> This is Paul
 over at the newsroom.</i>

58:26.604 --> 58:29.104
<i> What was that list of names
 again, please?</i>

58:29.106 --> 58:30.772
- One of the people
who came rushing

58:30.774 --> 58:35.244
into our newsroom
to help out was Paul Bolton.

58:35.246 --> 58:37.946
<i> He had gone
 into semi-retirement</i>

58:37.948 --> 58:40.249
<i> and I had taken over
 his position</i>

58:40.251 --> 58:42.784
<i> as the television
 news director.</i>

58:42.786 --> 58:45.254
Paul was working there
in the newsroom

58:45.256 --> 58:48.857
when Joe read
the list of names.

58:48.859 --> 58:52.995
And Paul reacted dramatically
at that point.

58:52.997 --> 58:55.297
<i>- Roy Schmidt, Billy Snowden--
- Joe, hold it.</i>

58:55.299 --> 58:56.899
<i> Hold just a minute.</i>

58:56.901 --> 58:58.901
<i> This is Paul
 over at the newsroom.</i>

58:58.903 --> 59:01.069
<i> Everyone is interested
 in that list of names.</i>

59:01.071 --> 59:03.539
<i> I think you have
 my grandson on there.</i>

59:03.541 --> 59:05.541
<i> Go over that list
 of names again, please.</i>

59:05.543 --> 59:06.875
- [sniffling]

59:12.550 --> 59:14.550
"I think you have my..."
[sniffles]

59:18.556 --> 59:22.558
"I think you have
my grandson.

59:22.560 --> 59:25.227
I think you have my grandson
on that list."

59:25.229 --> 59:26.895
Uh...

59:26.897 --> 59:29.565
And Joe said,
"Okay. Okay, I'll do that."

59:29.567 --> 59:31.900
And he went through the--
The list again.

59:31.902 --> 59:38.240
And, yeah, it was his namesake
grandson, Paul Bolton Sonntag.

59:38.242 --> 59:42.578
Didn't know at the time
if he'd been killed,

59:42.580 --> 59:44.079
but he was.

59:44.081 --> 59:48.650
Frankly,
I just broke up now.

59:48.652 --> 59:50.319
I think it's...
[laughs]

59:50.321 --> 59:52.187
I think it's because
I have grandchildren.

59:56.860 --> 01:00:01.063
<i> - I was in intensive care
 for seven weeks.</i>

01:00:05.069 --> 01:00:09.071
<i> Rita came to see me
 when I was in the hospital.</i>

01:00:09.073 --> 01:00:10.339
- How are you feeling?

01:00:16.213 --> 01:00:18.880
- I'm...[clears throat]

01:00:18.882 --> 01:00:20.882
I'm, uh...

01:00:20.884 --> 01:00:24.219
I'm doing better now.
- I made you something.

01:00:24.221 --> 01:00:26.888
It's nothing much.
I just...

01:00:26.890 --> 01:00:30.225
<i> - She came and brought me
 a painting she had done.</i>

01:00:37.067 --> 01:00:40.068
I was just, you know,
incredibly touched

01:00:40.070 --> 01:00:42.104
by her bringing that

01:00:42.106 --> 01:00:45.273
<i> and, um...I think
 that's the only time</i>

01:00:45.275 --> 01:00:47.876
we saw each other after that.

01:00:49.880 --> 01:00:53.115
<i>Only recently I've realized...</i>

01:00:54.885 --> 01:00:58.053
<i> How really, amazingly
 brave that was of her.</i>

01:00:58.055 --> 01:01:00.222
- Are you all right?
Let me help you.

01:01:00.224 --> 01:01:04.226
We've heard from all sorts
of people involved in this

01:01:04.228 --> 01:01:06.928
how terrified they were.

01:01:06.930 --> 01:01:10.265
<i> And yet she came
 right up to me.</i>

01:01:10.267 --> 01:01:13.268
<i> I mean,
 that was very selfless.</i>

01:01:15.272 --> 01:01:16.938
Why did you do that,
you know?

01:01:16.940 --> 01:01:18.940
What gave you the courage

01:01:18.942 --> 01:01:21.143
to come out and do that?

01:01:21.145 --> 01:01:23.078
<i> And were you afraid?</i>

01:01:23.080 --> 01:01:26.982
Were you afraid that
you were going to get killed?

01:01:28.152 --> 01:01:30.152
- For a person
to be so giving,

01:01:30.154 --> 01:01:33.388
has to go lay down
on hot concrete

01:01:33.390 --> 01:01:35.090
on a 100 degree day.

01:01:35.092 --> 01:01:37.759
<i> - Somehow, you know,
 that situation</i>

01:01:37.761 --> 01:01:40.929
<i> just pulled out
 that hero in her.</i>

01:01:46.103 --> 01:01:48.704
<i> - There's a special place
in Heaven for people like that.</i>

01:01:48.706 --> 01:01:51.440
She's a wonderful woman.

01:01:51.442 --> 01:01:55.143
<i> [office bustling]</i>

01:01:55.145 --> 01:01:57.245
<i> - As our various reporters
 and photographers</i>

01:01:57.247 --> 01:02:00.082
were bringing the film
back for processing,

01:02:00.084 --> 01:02:02.784
we were getting their stories
and their information.

01:02:02.786 --> 01:02:06.888
As we got a fuller picture
of where the damage was

01:02:06.890 --> 01:02:09.057
<i> and looked at the film,</i>

01:02:09.059 --> 01:02:11.760
it was even more horrifying...

01:02:13.430 --> 01:02:15.197
Than you could imagine.

01:02:15.199 --> 01:02:18.333
<i> - KTBC Television News
 now presents</i>

01:02:18.335 --> 01:02:21.036
<i> a special program
 on today's mass murder</i>

01:02:21.038 --> 01:02:22.838
<i> in the capital city.</i>

01:02:22.840 --> 01:02:25.841
<i> Here is KTBC Television
 News Editor, Neal Spelce.</i>

01:02:27.344 --> 01:02:29.177
- Good evening.
One of history's

01:02:29.179 --> 01:02:32.013
worst mass-murders occurred
here in Austin today.

01:02:32.015 --> 01:02:36.184
By official count tonight,
49 persons were hit by gunfire.

01:02:36.186 --> 01:02:39.187
There are 16 dead
and 33 injured.

01:02:39.189 --> 01:02:42.023
It started last night,
when a man reportedly

01:02:42.025 --> 01:02:43.492
killed his wife
and his mother.

01:02:43.494 --> 01:02:46.027
That same man apparently
rounded up an arsenal

01:02:46.029 --> 01:02:48.196
and supplies this morning
and then went

01:02:48.198 --> 01:02:51.366
<i> to the observation deck of
the University of Texas Tower.</i>

01:02:51.368 --> 01:02:54.136
It was then that terror
rained down from the Tower.

01:02:54.138 --> 01:02:56.271
<i> [gunfire]
 Charles J. Whitman</i>

01:02:56.273 --> 01:02:58.273
<i> was shot down
 on the observation deck</i>

01:02:58.275 --> 01:03:00.275
<i> by two city policemen.</i>

01:03:00.277 --> 01:03:03.445
The policemen were aided
by an Austin man, Allen Crum.

01:03:03.447 --> 01:03:06.548
<i> The story of how they ended
 the 90 minutes of terror</i>

01:03:06.550 --> 01:03:08.917
was told this afternoon
at a news conference

01:03:08.919 --> 01:03:11.186
held by Austin Police Chief
Bob Miles.

01:03:11.188 --> 01:03:12.921
- Did you guys shoot
as soon as you saw him?

01:03:12.923 --> 01:03:14.489
- Did anybody ask him
to surrender

01:03:14.491 --> 01:03:17.325
or give up or anything
before all the firing started?

01:03:17.327 --> 01:03:19.995
- No. As I said
just a moment ago,

01:03:19.997 --> 01:03:23.465
<i> Mr. Crum fired one shot
 into the west wall</i>

01:03:23.467 --> 01:03:26.301
When Officer Martinez
looked around the corner,

01:03:26.303 --> 01:03:29.304
Mr. Whitman had his gun
leveled out and ready to shoot.

01:03:29.306 --> 01:03:35.143
Officer Martinez had no way
of knowing whether Officer Day

01:03:35.145 --> 01:03:37.846
or Mr. Crum
had already come out

01:03:37.848 --> 01:03:39.080
and were in a position
to be shot.

01:03:41.418 --> 01:03:43.518
- At the news conference,
of course it was McCoy,

01:03:43.520 --> 01:03:46.521
<i> Jerry Day,
 Allen Crum, and myself.</i>

01:03:50.194 --> 01:03:51.560
- If you don't mind,

01:03:51.562 --> 01:03:53.428
I'll do the talking
for the group.

01:03:53.430 --> 01:03:57.098
And no. No.
And if I'm wrong,

01:03:57.100 --> 01:04:00.435
Mr. Martinez can stop me
and, uh, correct me on it.

01:04:00.437 --> 01:04:02.437
<i> - The reporters
 asked questions</i>

01:04:02.439 --> 01:04:05.874
<i> and Chief Miles answered
 all the questions.</i>

01:04:05.876 --> 01:04:08.143
<i> We were just there for
 show and tell, so to speak,</i>

01:04:08.145 --> 01:04:12.948
because he handled it.

01:04:12.950 --> 01:04:15.951
- The man here beside me
is Allen Crum.

01:04:15.953 --> 01:04:18.320
He was deputized
to go up on the Tower

01:04:18.322 --> 01:04:20.989
<i> with the two policemen
 who ended the gun battle.</i>

01:04:20.991 --> 01:04:22.924
- You got me?

01:04:22.926 --> 01:04:24.259
- I got you.

01:04:24.261 --> 01:04:26.595
- Mr. Crum, could you
tell us how you happened

01:04:26.597 --> 01:04:28.964
to be in the Tower building
in the first place?

01:04:28.966 --> 01:04:31.967
- Well I, uh...
[clears throat]

01:04:31.969 --> 01:04:33.969
Became involved in this
when I looked out

01:04:33.971 --> 01:04:36.571
of the Co-Op window and saw
a boy shot across the street.

01:04:36.573 --> 01:04:38.206
I went across the street
to investigate

01:04:38.208 --> 01:04:40.141
because I thought
it was a small fight.

01:04:40.143 --> 01:04:42.611
<i>And as I stepped out the door,
 I heard the sound of shots.</i>

01:04:42.613 --> 01:04:45.080
- And you actually
went into the Tower?

01:04:45.082 --> 01:04:47.482
- Yes, sir. I couldn't
get back across the street

01:04:47.484 --> 01:04:49.484
because of my fear
that I might get shot myself.

01:04:49.486 --> 01:04:53.889
So I went to the next building,
and the next building.

01:04:53.891 --> 01:04:55.891
I thought perhaps I could help
them when I got over there

01:04:55.893 --> 01:04:57.893
so I waited 'till he shot
from the other side of the Tower

01:04:57.895 --> 01:04:59.227
<i> and then ran into it myself.</i>

01:04:59.229 --> 01:05:00.562
<i> - Mr. Crum,
 I know that I speak</i>

01:05:00.564 --> 01:05:03.899
for all the citizens
of Austin in expressing

01:05:03.901 --> 01:05:05.133
our gratitude to you

01:05:05.135 --> 01:05:07.369
and to the Austin
police officers

01:05:07.371 --> 01:05:10.205
who put an end
to the reign of terror

01:05:10.207 --> 01:05:11.539
on the University
of Texas campus.

01:05:11.541 --> 01:05:14.509
- I've never known
braver men.

01:05:14.511 --> 01:05:16.945
<i> Their decisions
 were correct,</i>

01:05:16.947 --> 01:05:19.080
<i> timely done,</i>

01:05:19.082 --> 01:05:22.417
and accomplished in an honorable
manner.

01:05:22.419 --> 01:05:25.253
If I had to do this
over again with these men,

01:05:25.255 --> 01:05:27.122
<i> I certainly would.</i>

01:05:27.124 --> 01:05:29.691
<i> The Chief of Police
 offered me a check</i>

01:05:29.693 --> 01:05:31.359
from the City of Austin

01:05:31.361 --> 01:05:34.396
for one day's
deputized citizen's pay.

01:05:36.566 --> 01:05:38.566
<i> I refused it, of course.</i>

01:05:41.571 --> 01:05:44.439
<i> - Somehow, we ended up
 out on Airport Boulevard</i>

01:05:44.441 --> 01:05:48.510
<i> in a vacant lot
with a case of Lone Star beer.</i>

01:05:48.512 --> 01:05:50.512
<i> Took off our weapons,</i>

01:05:50.514 --> 01:05:53.181
<i> still dressed in our blues
and everything like that but...</i>

01:05:55.519 --> 01:05:57.652
<i> We wasn't policemen no more.</i>

01:06:03.660 --> 01:06:06.728
<i> If I would have just gone in,
 if I had just gone</i>

01:06:06.730 --> 01:06:08.596
<i> right up to that elevator,</i>

01:06:08.598 --> 01:06:10.532
pressed that button
to the top floor...

01:06:14.538 --> 01:06:16.271
Gone in and get him done.

01:06:16.273 --> 01:06:19.274
- Go up and get him done,

01:06:19.276 --> 01:06:21.276
then Billy Speed
would still be alive.

01:06:21.278 --> 01:06:22.577
- Billy!

01:06:22.579 --> 01:06:24.579
- And a lot of other,
I'm sure, but...

01:06:26.583 --> 01:06:30.285
But-but-but...
didn't happen that way.

01:06:33.023 --> 01:06:34.189
- [sighs]

01:06:34.191 --> 01:06:36.358
Shoulda-coulda.
[chuckles]

01:06:37.527 --> 01:06:39.995
But I didn't.

01:06:43.533 --> 01:06:45.700
- Shoulda, coulda. Shoulda...

01:06:45.702 --> 01:06:48.703
Shoulda, coulda.
But didn't.

01:06:48.705 --> 01:06:53.742
So...I don't know.

01:06:58.115 --> 01:07:01.116
<i> - Well, to say it hasn't
 affected me in my life,</i>

01:07:01.118 --> 01:07:04.486
it wouldn't be
a truthful statement.

01:07:04.488 --> 01:07:07.322
But I have, um...

01:07:07.324 --> 01:07:09.324
tried.

01:07:09.326 --> 01:07:12.494
I have tried
to just forget it.

01:07:12.496 --> 01:07:14.496
<i> I hate to see people
 get hurt.</i>

01:07:14.498 --> 01:07:17.165
But, you know,
you have to be realistic

01:07:17.167 --> 01:07:19.134
and know that these things
are gonna happen.

01:07:19.136 --> 01:07:22.037
And so you have to have the way
how to cope with it,

01:07:22.039 --> 01:07:24.039
how to take care
of the problems.

01:07:29.212 --> 01:07:31.579
<i> - If somebody were
 to ask how you feel,</i>

01:07:31.581 --> 01:07:33.448
<i> well...</i>

01:07:34.785 --> 01:07:37.652
Well, I'd say no words.

01:07:37.654 --> 01:07:39.387
It's something--
I've been asked that before,

01:07:39.389 --> 01:07:42.057
How-how did it
make you feel?

01:07:42.059 --> 01:07:44.726
And then I kinda
have to say, "Well...

01:07:44.728 --> 01:07:47.562
"How would I describe
the colors of a rainbow

01:07:47.564 --> 01:07:50.532
to a person born blind?"

01:07:50.534 --> 01:07:53.068
<i> You can't,
 'cause there ain't no words.</i>

01:07:54.237 --> 01:07:56.237
Uh, I don't know.

01:08:02.579 --> 01:08:07.449
- This is the shirt
that I was wearing.

01:08:07.451 --> 01:08:11.619
And I must've weighed
about 90 pounds when...

01:08:11.621 --> 01:08:14.522
When this shooting happened.

01:08:14.524 --> 01:08:17.292
See that little tear
right there?

01:08:17.294 --> 01:08:19.294
<i>It's where the bullet
just kinda pew.</i>

01:08:19.296 --> 01:08:21.662
<i> [gunshot]</i>

01:08:21.665 --> 01:08:23.665
This is my cousin,
Lee Zamora.

01:08:23.667 --> 01:08:26.667
He was with me
when I was riding the bicycle

01:08:26.670 --> 01:08:30.638
and delivering newspapers at
the University of Texas Tower.

01:08:32.142 --> 01:08:34.142
<i> - I was just thinking,
 you know,</i>

01:08:34.144 --> 01:08:37.178
I've never talked to anyone
about this before.

01:08:37.180 --> 01:08:39.481
<i> [gunshot]</i>

01:08:39.483 --> 01:08:41.349
<i> [gunshot]
And I thought, you know,</i>

01:08:41.350 --> 01:08:45.520
maybe it'll help me,
you know, do some good

01:08:45.522 --> 01:08:50.492
to sit and talk about it
to someone, you know, for once.

01:08:50.493 --> 01:08:51.826
Maybe it's something
I need to do.

01:08:55.599 --> 01:08:59.134
- If you folks had not
given us this opportunity,

01:08:59.136 --> 01:09:03.638
I would not have seen
this cousin of mine. I do now.

01:09:03.640 --> 01:09:08.542
Been a long time.
I mean, almost 50 years.

01:09:12.682 --> 01:09:14.782
- It was just
a whole different world.

01:09:16.286 --> 01:09:18.720
<i> Nobody ever talked about it.</i>

01:09:18.721 --> 01:09:21.221
- I didn't meet Claire

01:09:21.224 --> 01:09:23.858
until, uh, a few months ago.

01:09:26.529 --> 01:09:28.595
<i> - I never knew
 who Artly was.</i>

01:09:28.598 --> 01:09:31.899
I finally decided maybe he was
just an angel or something.

01:09:39.276 --> 01:09:41.876
- I was 17.
I'd never seen death.

01:09:41.877 --> 01:09:43.877
I didn't know
anything about guns.

01:09:43.880 --> 01:09:48.216
It was nothing but a big,
raw, gaping wound,

01:09:48.218 --> 01:09:50.952
you know, in my psyche.
In my memory.

01:09:50.953 --> 01:09:52.587
There has been
a passage of time, and...

01:09:52.589 --> 01:09:55.823
[stuttering]

01:09:55.825 --> 01:09:58.459
It's still raw, but it's not
as raw as it once was.

01:09:59.462 --> 01:10:00.795
A lotta times,

01:10:00.797 --> 01:10:03.731
the worst days
of your lives are...

01:10:03.733 --> 01:10:07.402
personal and, uh, private.

01:10:07.404 --> 01:10:09.404
Maybe that's why I've...
I sort of...

01:10:09.406 --> 01:10:12.740
[stutters]

01:10:12.742 --> 01:10:14.475
Um, hid it inside.

01:10:17.814 --> 01:10:20.348
<i> I feel guilty because
 I didn't go out soon enough.</i>

01:10:20.350 --> 01:10:22.984
- Oh, Artly.
- You know, that you were...

01:10:22.986 --> 01:10:24.686
- Artly.
[laughs]

01:10:24.688 --> 01:10:26.621
- Yeah, it's just--
I think--I think guilt

01:10:26.623 --> 01:10:29.457
comes with events like this.
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:10:29.459 --> 01:10:31.559
- Strange guilt.

01:10:35.565 --> 01:10:39.334
<i> UT was closed for one day.
 That was it.</i>

01:10:39.336 --> 01:10:41.336
<i> They came in
 and cleaned up the blood.</i>

01:10:43.840 --> 01:10:49.244
I think the university
should put up a memorial.

01:10:49.246 --> 01:10:52.847
There's still lots of family
and lots of friends

01:10:52.849 --> 01:10:54.849
<i> of people that were
 killed and injured.</i>

01:10:56.853 --> 01:11:00.521
- Paul Sonntag,
Claudia Rutt,

01:11:00.523 --> 01:11:03.992
Robert Boyer,
Billy Speed,

01:11:03.994 --> 01:11:07.862
Roy Schmidt,
Edna Townsley,

01:11:07.864 --> 01:11:12.400
Marguerite Lamport,
Mark Gabour,

01:11:12.402 --> 01:11:16.904
Thomas Eckman,
Harry Walchuk,

01:11:16.906 --> 01:11:20.041
Thomas Ashton,
Thomas Karr,

01:11:20.043 --> 01:11:23.745
Karen Griffith,
David Gunby,

01:11:23.747 --> 01:11:25.747
and my baby.

01:11:28.918 --> 01:11:33.621
They said I could have babies,
but I never got pregnant.

01:11:34.624 --> 01:11:37.458
But I got to adopt my child.

01:11:37.460 --> 01:11:39.694
<i> I adopted my child Sirak.</i>

01:11:39.696 --> 01:11:41.696
<i> He was born in Ethiopia</i>

01:11:41.698 --> 01:11:44.866
<i> and I adopted him
 when he was four.</i>

01:11:44.868 --> 01:11:47.869
<i> And he's now 27.</i>

01:11:47.871 --> 01:11:51.372
I mean, Sirak
was a wonderful child.

01:11:51.374 --> 01:11:53.374
And there are times,
even though

01:11:53.376 --> 01:11:55.610
his skin is brown
and mine's white,

01:11:55.612 --> 01:11:59.447
there are times when
I absolutely cannot remember

01:11:59.449 --> 01:12:02.717
<i> that he didn't
 come out of me.</i>

01:12:02.719 --> 01:12:07.722
But the baby...
I-I dreamed about him

01:12:07.724 --> 01:12:11.059
from the beginning
and I still have dreams

01:12:11.061 --> 01:12:15.063
that I found him
and I have him

01:12:15.065 --> 01:12:17.598
<i> and I'm so happy.</i>

01:12:17.600 --> 01:12:21.069
But then I'd look away
or something and he's gone.

01:12:24.941 --> 01:12:26.941
<i> [gunshots]</i>

01:12:30.780 --> 01:12:33.081
<i> - I remember looking
at the Tower, of course, a lot.</i>

01:12:33.083 --> 01:12:35.616
And from the Main Mall,
you can see

01:12:35.618 --> 01:12:38.786
there's a biblical line
from the Bible.

01:12:38.788 --> 01:12:40.788
<i> "Ye shall know the truth and
the truth shall make you free."</i>

01:12:40.790 --> 01:12:42.623
<i> [gunshot]</i>

01:12:42.625 --> 01:12:46.060
I've thought about it.
[sniffles]

01:12:46.062 --> 01:12:47.929
One of the truths I learned...

01:12:50.433 --> 01:12:52.934
Is that there are monsters
that walk among us.

01:12:52.936 --> 01:12:54.769
<i> [sirens wailing]</i>

01:12:54.771 --> 01:12:58.706
There are people out there
that think unthinkable thoughts

01:12:58.708 --> 01:13:00.708
<i> and then do
 unthinkable things.</i>

01:13:06.750 --> 01:13:09.016
<i> - Through the years,
 he remained</i>

01:13:09.018 --> 01:13:12.520
largely kind of wooden
in my mind.

01:13:12.522 --> 01:13:16.157
But the longer I've lived
and the more I've seen,

01:13:16.159 --> 01:13:19.427
these precious little children
who grow up

01:13:19.429 --> 01:13:21.996
and do sometimes
horrible things,

01:13:21.998 --> 01:13:25.500
<i> the more I have come
 to think of him</i>

01:13:25.502 --> 01:13:29.137
<i> as a very confused,
 very damaged young man.</i>

01:13:29.139 --> 01:13:32.039
<i> He died at about 25.</i>

01:13:32.041 --> 01:13:36.544
There's a picture of him
standing at three years old,

01:13:36.546 --> 01:13:40.782
holding a rifle on either side
on the beach.

01:13:40.784 --> 01:13:43.785
I just think of him when
he was that three-year-old

01:13:43.787 --> 01:13:47.054
who would have been sitting
in my lap, you know.

01:13:47.056 --> 01:13:51.559
I'm a teacher,
and I love that age.

01:13:51.561 --> 01:13:54.061
So much promise
and so much hope.

01:13:55.899 --> 01:13:59.033
How can I hate
somebody like that?

01:13:59.035 --> 01:14:00.568
I can't hate him,
in spite

01:14:00.570 --> 01:14:04.639
of the incredible damage
that he's done.

01:14:04.641 --> 01:14:06.974
I can't hate him.
I just can't do that.

01:14:08.978 --> 01:14:12.747
<i> - Do you forgive him?
- I forgive him, yes.</i>

01:14:12.749 --> 01:14:15.917
How can I not forgive?
I've been forgiven so much.

01:14:17.854 --> 01:14:20.855
<i> [slow rock music]</i>

01:14:20.857 --> 01:14:27.528
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

01:14:27.530 --> 01:14:29.530
- The horror of these,
the sick among us,

01:14:29.532 --> 01:14:33.534
must be found in the horror
of our hyper civilization.

01:14:33.536 --> 01:14:37.538
A strange pandering to violence,
a disrespect for life

01:14:37.540 --> 01:14:39.707
fostered in part by
governments which,

01:14:39.709 --> 01:14:42.143
in pursuit of the doctrine
of self-defense,

01:14:42.145 --> 01:14:45.513
teach their youth to kill
and to maim.

01:14:45.515 --> 01:14:47.515
<i> A society in which
 the most popular</i>

01:14:47.517 --> 01:14:50.852
<i> newspaper cartoon strips,
 television programs,</i>

01:14:50.854 --> 01:14:53.120
<i> and movies are those
 that can invent</i>

01:14:53.122 --> 01:14:56.557
<i> new means of perpetrating
 bodily harm.</i>

01:14:56.559 --> 01:14:59.126
<i> A people who somehow
 can remain silent</i>

01:14:59.128 --> 01:15:02.129
<i> while their own civilization
 seems to crumble</i>

01:15:02.131 --> 01:15:05.132
<i> under the force of the
 caveman's philosophy--</i>

01:15:05.134 --> 01:15:07.802
<i> That might makes right.</i>

01:15:07.804 --> 01:15:11.806
It seems likely that
Charles Joseph Whitman's crime

01:15:11.808 --> 01:15:14.141
was society's crime.

01:15:14.143 --> 01:15:17.144
This is Walter Cronkite.
Good night.

